Set B1 (answer at least one question)
1. LC uses a number of variables to determine the pricing for its loans. Review and attempt to explain the relationship between the
  1. sub_grade
  2. the int_rate
  3. the loan_amnt, and d) the loan term (variable= term).

It seems that there are some linear relations betweens “sub_grade” and “the int_rate”. It also seems there are some patterns between “loan_ammounts”" and “sub_grade”.

Let us make a closer inspection between each pair of variables:

  1. Relation between “int_rate incease” and “sub_grades”:
# plot the mean of int_rate for each sub_grade
te<-data.frame(sub_grade=levels(datab1$sub_grade),int_rate_mean=with(datab1, tapply(int_rate, sub_grade, mean)), loan_amnt_mean=with(datab1, tapply(loan_amnt, sub_grade, mean)))

qplot(sub_grade, int_rate_mean, data = te, geom = "boxplot", color = sub_grade) +
  xlab(toupper("SUB_GRADES")) +
  ylab("INT_RATE") +
  ggtitle("AVERAGE INT_RATE VS. LC SUB_GRADES")

  1. Relation between “term” and “sub_grades”:
ggplot(datab1,aes(x=sub_grade))+ geom_bar(aes(fill = term, stat = "identity"), position = "fill")

ggplot(datab1,aes(x=sub_grade,y=loan_amnt,fill=sub_grade))+geom_boxplot()

#Using Chi-square test and Cramer V to test the significant relationship between term(categorical) and sub_grade(categorical)
tb = table(datab1$sub_grade,datab1$term) 
chisq.test(tb) 
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  tb
## X-squared = 86391, df = 34, p-value < 2.2e-16
cv.test = function(x,y) {
  CV = sqrt(chisq.test(x, y, correct=FALSE)$statistic /
    (length(x) * (min(length(unique(x)),length(unique(y))) - 1)))
  print.noquote("Cramér V / Phi:")
  return(as.numeric(CV))
}
cv.test(datab1$sub_grade,datab1$term)
## [1] Cramer V / Phi:
## [1] 0.4529448

From the plots, we can see that the percentage of observation of 60 months term has increased from “sub_grades” A1 to G5.
From the Chi-square test, we can see that the p-value is very small, which implies that the correlation between variables is significant, and that Cramer V / Phi shows a normal strength of correlation.

Set B2 (answer at least one question)
1. The LC risk model has assigned records to different pricing tiers, indicated within the sub_grade variable. Using the sub_grade as the dependent variable, determine which other variables are most related/predictive and attempt to explain why.

There are various ways that can help us find the strong predictors of sub_grade, for example:

  1. Run the logistic regression model and inspect the p-value of each Xi. A lower p-value means a significant relationship.(Remember to use VIF to check the colinear issues.)
  2. After building the regression model, implement stepwise model selection, using backward, forward, stepwise to select the best set of predictors with lowest performance index, eg. AIC, BIC.
  3. Inspect the correlation between Y and Xi to obtain the candidates of predictors which have significant relationships. But be aware that this is just a preliminary test as the true relation still would still consider the spurious correlation and collinearity in the further analysis.
  4. Use the decision tree to build a classification model and inspect the node’s variable which brings a significant pruning impact.

In this case, first I will do the preliminary correlation testing with ANOVA and Chi-square:

#Due to our target sub_grade as categorical variables, I will use ANOVA and Chi-square testing to inspect the relationship between predictors and our target, "sub_grade"
data2<-data[ , !(names(data) %in% c("sub_grade"))]
datatype<-sapply(data, class)
data_cate<-data2[sapply(data2,is.factor)] # factor type predictors 
data_num<-data2[sapply(data2,is.numeric)] # numerica type predictors
cor_cate<-apply(data_cate,2, function(col) chisq.test(table(col, data$sub_grade))$p.value) # chisq-test
corall<-append(cor_cate,cor_num) # Get all p-value of correlations

By using ANOVA and Chi-square testing, inspect the relation between predictors and “sub_grade”" so that we can rank the significance of relationship. Top ten candidates with significant relationships are(lowest p-value):

names(sort.int(corall))[1:10]
##  [1] "term"                "int_rate"            "grade"              
##  [4] "home_ownership"      "annual_inc"          "verification_status"
##  [7] "issue_d"             "loan_status"         "purpose"            
## [10] "title"

Please note that this is only a rough test as we still have to consider the spurious correlation and collinearity of each predictos in a further analysis. I also strongly recommend discussing with domain experts and to do the graph analysis to make the final manual model selection more suitable for real world cases.

Now, I am going to run the logistic regression to build the predicted model and find the strong predictors:

#Clean the data first

#Find the variable which has too many levels or missing data or one with only one level. In general, I will suggest trying to reduce the dimension by bining, but in this case, I will delete them.

dl<-sapply(data, function(x) nlevels(x))
data2=data[,-which(dl>100 | dl==1)]
dl<-sapply(data2, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
data2<-data2[,-which(dl>20)]
data2<-na.omit(data2)
data2<-data2[ , !(names(data2) %in% c("pymnt_plan","desc","initial_list_status","application_type","verification_status_joint","policy_code"))]

#In this case, due to the computing limit, I will only take 1% sample data to find the strong predictors.
set.seed(1)
spt<-sample(1:nrow(data2),nrow(data2)*0.01)
data3=data2[spt,]
tp<-sample(2,nrow(data3),replace = T, prob=c(0.7,0.3))
training<-data3[tp==1,x]
test<-data3[tp==2,x]
fit<-glm(sub_grade~.,training)
summary(fit)
